-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - July 16
-- By Clare Jim
-- Tue Jul 15, 2014 09:20PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 16 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Wednesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST -- Macau's leader said he would be "happy" to let Beijing know what the city's residents think about democracy, as he launched his campaign for re-election as chief executive, an exercise all too likely to be a one-man race. The promise drew criticism that Dr Fernando Chui Sai-on was merely paying lip service to increasingly disaffected and democratically minded young people. [ID:nNrm9R07xz] -- Legislation doubling the stamp duty on most property purchases was finally passed by lawmakers on Tuesday night, just before the Legislative Council enters its three-month summer recess. [ID:nNrm8Y46vr] -- Four of the 10 developers invited to tender by the Urban Renewal Authority (URA) have submitted bids for the Kwun Tong redevelopment project, which could see an estimated investment of HK$18 billion ($2.32 billion). [ID:nNrm9xdfNf] -- Kaisa Group Holdings Ltd <1638.HK>, a leader in mainland urban redevelopment projects, said it would be able to hit its sales target of 30 billion yuan ($4.83 billion) this year and maintain a gross margin of 30 to 35 percent in the next few years despite market volatility. [ID:nNrmb95lW7]  THE STANDARD -- Zoomlion Heavy Industry Science and Technology <000157.SZ><1157.HK> told analysts it rejected around 15 percent of new orders for truck-mounted concrete pumps in the first half, fearing that China's property market slowdown would hit customers' ability to pay for them. (http://bit.ly/1rpeN4m) -- Around 10,000 nurses, patients and their families signed a petition calling on the health secretary to make "substantial improvements" to address Hong Kong's shortage of nurses. (http://bit.ly/1mIPj1f)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Sales of luxury apartments priced above HK$12 million ($1.55 million) declined 8.2 percent in the first half from six months ago, according to data from realtor Centaline Property, the lowest since the financial crisis in 2008, hurt by the double stamp duty.   HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES -- There are fewer than 10 apartments priced below HK$3 million for sale in large housing estates in Hong Kong, and their price per sq ft has risen above HK$10,000.